<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-918-932  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 918 932.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 27 1989 v23 n48 p95(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Arms and the IS manager. (information-systems management atdefense contractors)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ludlum, David A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Cuts in defense spending and peace efforts between thesuperpowers, along with a narrowing of the technological gapbetween US defense contractors and their foreign counterparts, arelikely to result in slower sales and fewer job opportunities.andO;Major contractors say that they have already acted to address thedecline in demand for their products; few expect any dramaticchange, but restructuring may bring about some new careeropportunities for information-systems managers.andP;  The AerospaceIndustry Association projected a decline in employment among USmilitary-aircraft makers.andP;  Lockheed Corp says it expects thenumber of information-systems management positions to eitherdecline or remain stable in the near future; other firms say newopenings are unlikely, but many opportunities are expected formanagers already within companies as globalization and systemsintegration become issues.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Job SearchEmployment OpportunityCareer DevelopmentMilitaryOutlook.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>